Theory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Langevin equations describing the stochastic trajectories of the colloids
 are
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
m_{i}\dot{\boldsymbol{v}_{i}} & +\boldsymbol{\gamma}_{ij}\cdot\boldsymbol{v}_{j}+{\bf \boldsymbol{\nabla}}_{i}U=\boldsymbol{{\bf \xi}}_{i}\label{eq1}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j=1,2$
\end_inset

 refer to the driving and driven colloid, 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{i}$
\end_inset

 are their masses, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{v}_{i}$
\end_inset

 are their velocities, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\gamma}_{ij}$
\end_inset

 are the second-rank friction tensors encoding the velocity-dependent dissipativ
e forces mediated by the fluid, 
\begin_inset Formula $U=U_{1}+U_{2}$
\end_inset

 is the total potential of the conservative forces, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\xi}_{i}$
\end_inset

, the Langevin noises, are zero-mean Gaussian random variables whose variance
 is provided by the fluctuation-dissipation relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\boldsymbol{\xi}_{i}(t)\boldsymbol{\xi}_{j}(t^{\prime})\rangle=2k_{B}T\boldsymbol{\gamma}_{ij}\delta(t-t^{\prime})$
\end_inset

.
 The bold-face notation, with Cartesian indices suppressed, is used for
 both vectors and tensors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the limit of slow viscous flow in the fluid, the friction tensors can
 be calculated from the Stokes equation using a variety of methods.
 To leading order the result is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{\gamma}_{ij}=\delta_{ij}\boldsymbol{I}\gamma_{i}-(1-\delta_{ij})\gamma_{i}\gamma_{j}\mathcal{F}_{i}\mathcal{F}_{j}\boldsymbol{G}(\boldsymbol{r}_{i},\boldsymbol{r}_{j})
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{i}=6\pi\eta a_{i}$
\end_inset

 are the self-frictions, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{G}$
\end_inset

 is a Green's function of the Stokes equation, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{r}_{i}$
\end_inset

 are the centers of the colloids and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{i}=1+\frac{a_{i}^{2}}{6}\nabla_{i}^{2}$
\end_inset

 are the Faxen corrections that account for the finite radius, 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}$
\end_inset

, of the colloids.
 We emphasize that this expression is not limited to the translationally
 invariant Green's function of unbounded flow, 
\begin_inset Formula $8\pi\eta\,\boldsymbol{G}(\boldsymbol{r})=(\nabla^{2}\boldsymbol{I}-\boldsymbol{\nabla\nabla})r$
\end_inset

, but holds generally for any Green's function and is both symmetric and
 positive-definite.
 The mutual friction tensors decay inversely with distance in an unbounded
 fluid and more rapidly in the proximity of boundaries.
 The assumption of slow viscous flow is valid at frequencies 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\tau_{\nu}\ll1$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{\nu}=\rho L^{2}/\eta$
\end_inset

 is the vorticity diffusion time scale.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The harmonic optical potentials are given by 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}(t)=\frac{1}{2}k_{i}|{\bf \boldsymbol{r}}_{i}-{\bf \boldsymbol{r}}_{i}^{0}|^{2}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{r}_{i}^{0}$
\end_inset

 are the centers and 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{i}$
\end_inset

 are the stiffnesses of the optical traps.
 Note the absence of conservative mutual couplings.
 The system remains in equilibrium when the trap centers are stationary
 but is driven into non-equilibrium when they are modulated in time as 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{r}_{i}^{0}(t)$
\end_inset

.
 For small modulations the response is linear.
 
\end_layout

