\begin_layout Standard
In the experimental set-up, we have two such optical traps with the minimum
 of one of them is being shifted with an external periodic signal, and the
 response of the two beads studied.
 Assuming momentum to be rapidly relaxing on the time scale of the trap
 motion, we neglect inertia and average over the noise to get, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
-\gamma_{ij}{\bf \dot{R}}_{j}-{\bf \nabla_{i}U}=0\label{eq2}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Eq.
\begin_inset Formula $\ref{eq2}$
\end_inset

 can be inverted and presented in terms of mobility matrices as, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
{\bf \dot{R}}_{1} & =-\mu{\bf \delta}k_{1}({\bf R}_{1}-{\bf R}_{1}^{0})-{\bf \mu_{12}}k_{2}({\bf R}_{2}-{\bf R}_{2}^{0})\label{eq3}\\
{\bf \dot{R}}_{2} & =-{\bf \mu_{21}}k_{1}({\bf R}_{1}-{\bf R}_{1}^{0})-\mu{\bf \delta}k_{2}({\bf R}_{2}-{\bf R}_{2}^{0})\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

We re-frame this equation using approximate mobility matrices with the separatio
n vector to be the average distance between the two minima of the optical
 traps.
 Thus, one obtains, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{d}{dt}\begin{bmatrix}{\bf R}_{1}\\
{\bf R}_{2}
\end{bmatrix}=-\begin{bmatrix}\mu k_{1}{\bf \delta} & {\bf \mu}_{12}k_{2}\\
{\bf \mu}_{21}k_{1} & \mu k_{2}{\bf \delta}
\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}{\bf R}_{1}\\
{\bf R}_{2}
\end{bmatrix}+\begin{bmatrix}\mu{\bf \delta} & {\bf \mu}_{12}\\
{\bf \mu}_{21} & \mu\delta
\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}{\bf F}_{1}^{0}\\
{\bf F}_{2}^{0}
\end{bmatrix}\label{eq4}
\end{align}

\end_inset

The steady state solution of the Eq.
\begin_inset Formula $\ref{eq4}$
\end_inset

 can easily be calculated by taking its Fourier transform.
 Assuming 
\begin_inset Formula ${\bf A}=\begin{bmatrix}\mu k_{1}{\bf \delta} & {\bf \mu}_{12}k_{2}\\
{\bf \mu}_{21}k_{1} & \mu k_{2}{\bf \delta}
\end{bmatrix}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula ${\bf M}=\begin{bmatrix}\mu{\bf \delta} & {\bf \mu}_{12}\\
{\bf \mu}_{21} & \mu\delta
\end{bmatrix}$
\end_inset

, the solution in frequency domain is given by, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
{\bf R}_{i}(\omega)=[-i\omega{\bf \delta}+{\bf A}]_{ij}^{-1}{\bf M}{\bf F}_{j}^{0}(\omega)={\bf \chi_{ij}}(\omega){\bf F}_{j}^{0}(\omega)\label{eq5}
\end{align}

\end_inset

which defines the response for 
\begin_inset Formula ${\chi}$
\end_inset

.
 As the minimum of one of the optical traps is modulated by a sinusoidal
 signal of driving frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula ${\bf F}_{j}^{0}(\omega)=\frac{X_{j}}{2}(\delta(\omega-\Omega)+\delta(\omega+\Omega))$
\end_inset

.
 Further, 
\begin_inset Formula ${\bf \chi}$
\end_inset

 is a block-diagonal matrix in cartesian indices.
 Now, for a given experimental set-up, 
\begin_inset Formula ${\bf \chi}$
\end_inset

 can be decomposed into 
\begin_inset Formula ${\bf \chi_{\parallel}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula ${\bf \chi_{\perp}}$
\end_inset

, which correspond to motion along the trap separation and that perpendicular
 to it, respectively.
 Inserting this form of the signal into Eq.
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq5"

\end_inset

, and reverting to the time domain, we find 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
R_{\parallel i}(t)=\chi'_{\parallel ij}\cos(\Omega t)X_{j}+\chi"_{\parallel ij}\sin(\Omega t)X_{j}\label{eq6}
\end{align}

\end_inset

The two time scales from the two traps can be calculated to be 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{i}=\frac{1}{\mu k_{i}}$
\end_inset

, so that, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
{\bf \chi}_{\parallel}(\Omega)=\frac{1}{DetA_{\parallel}-\Omega^{2}-i\Omega TrA_{\parallel}}\times\\
\begin{bmatrix}(\mu k_{1}-i\Omega) & \mu_{12}k_{2}\\
\mu_{21}k_{1} & (\mu k_{2}-i\Omega)
\end{bmatrix}^{-1}\begin{bmatrix}\mu & \mu_{12}\\
\mu_{21} & \mu
\end{bmatrix}\\
=\frac{1}{DetA_{\parallel}-\Omega^{2}-i\Omega TrA_{\parallel}}\times\\
\begin{bmatrix}(\mu k_{2}-i\Omega) & -\mu_{12}k_{2}\\
-\mu_{21}k_{1} & (\mu k_{1}-i\Omega)
\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}\mu & \mu_{12}\\
\mu_{21} & \mu
\end{bmatrix}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
=\frac{DetA_{\parallel}-\Omega^{2}+i\Omega TrA_{\parallel}}{(DetA_{\parallel}-\Omega^{2})^{2}+\Omega^{2}(TrA_{\parallel})^{2}}\times\nonumber \\
\begin{bmatrix}k_{2}DetM_{\parallel}-i\mu\Omega & -i\Omega\mu_{12}\\
-i\Omega\mu_{21} & k_{1}DetM_{\parallel}-i\mu\Omega
\end{bmatrix}\label{eq7}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
=(DetA_{\parallel}-\Omega^{2})^{2}+\Omega^{2}(TrA_{\parallel})^{2}\times\nonumber \\
\begin{bmatrix}\mu k_{2}^{2}DetM_{\parallel}+\mu\Omega^{2} & -(DetA_{\parallel}-\Omega^{2})\mu_{12}\\
-(DetA_{\parallel}-\Omega^{2})\mu_{21} & \mu k_{1}^{2}DetM_{\parallel}+\mu\Omega^{2}
\end{bmatrix}\label{eq8}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that we are interested in the resonance in amplitude of the second
 bead due to the forcing of the first bead that is given by maximizing the
 modulus of 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{21\parallel}$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mid\chi_{21\parallel}\mid & =\mid\frac{-i\Omega\mu_{21}}{DetA_{\parallel}-\Omega^{2}-i\Omega TrA_{\parallel}}\mid\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{\Omega\mu_{21}}{\sqrt{(DetA_{\parallel}-\Omega^{2})^{2}+\Omega^{2}(TrA_{\parallel})^{2}}}\label{eq9}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Clearly the resonance frequency in dimensionless unit is 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{1}\Omega_{res}=\sqrt{\frac{DetA_{\parallel}}{\mu^{2}k_{1}^{2}}}=\sqrt{\frac{k_{2}}{k_{1}}\left(1-\frac{\mu_{\parallel12}^{2}}{\mu^{2}}\right)}$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{21}\neq0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

